Project Title: Public Gardens as Sentinels against Invasive Plants
additionalCollectorNotes: Seeds excessively and can be difficult to remove due to traproot; resrpouts from root if less than 50% of root is removed. Large seed bank in the soil. Took several seasons to remove from Rock Alpine and still not fully gone as of 2020. Seems to develop some herbicide resistance if not killed by first spraying. As of 2020 there is a chemically resistant population in the Rock Garden. Mike Kintgen put this on internal list in 2014 and still feels it has merit in 2020. Has been treated since 2006. Over 10 years of treatment at DBG. Seed.
locality: Denver Botanic Gardens. 909 York Street. Rock Alpine Garden, Lower Meadow.

Project Title: Public Gardens as Sentinels against Invasive Plants
additionalCollectorNotes: Seeds profusely in garden setting. Very difficult to dig/remove due to small bulblets that multiply. Spread predominantly vegetative.
locality: Denver Botanic Gardens. 909 York Street. Water Smart Garden, Ext Bed 3.

Project Title: Public Gardens as Sentinels against Invasive Plants
additionalCollectorNotes: Bulblets produced underground from larger bulb and aerial bulblets present around flowers. There is also a sterile flower form that does not produce the bulblets. Spreads aggressively. Spread by seed and vegetatively.
locality: Denver Botanic Gardens. 909 York Street. Lobby Entrance, Ramp Bed.

Project Title: Public Gardens as Sentinels against Invasive Plants
additionalCollectorNotes: Uncommon weed found in fields and gardens in Denver and Boulder Counties (Ackerfield 2015). Reseeds heavily in the Rock Alpine Garden. Removed in 2006 and still persists in 2021. Spread by seed.
locality: Denver Botanic Gardens. 909 York Street. Rock Alpine Garden.

Project Title: Public Gardens as Sentinels against Invasive Plants
additionalCollectorNotes: Strong, deep taproot makes removal difficult. Can resprout from roots. Cutting and spraying since 2010 has failed to eradicate as of 2021. Predominantly spreads by seed but can send runners that form small colonies.
locality: Denver Botanic Gardens. 909 York Street. Rock Alpine Garden Upper Meadow.

Project Title: Public Gardens as Sentinels against Invasive Plants
locality: Denver Botanic Gardens. 909 York Street. Water Smart Garden.

Project Title: Public Gardens as Sentinels against Invasive Plants
additionalCollectorNotes: Observed naturalizing along the High Line Canal and Cherry Creek in Denver County. Seedlings mildly resistant to 2,4-D in a garden setting. Reseeds heavily.
locality: Denver Botanic Gardens. 909 York Street. Woodland Mosaic Bed 9.

Project Title: Public Gardens as Sentinels against Invasive Plants
additionalCollectorNotes: Management by spraying, deadheading, and hand-digging from 2006 to 2021 has not successfully controlled this species in the Rock Alpine Garden. Also present in the Woodland Mosaic and Plant Asia Gardens. Removed from Plant Select due to its potential invasiveness. Reseeds heavily into established vegetation. Not rhizomatous.
locality: Denver Botanic Gardens. 909 York Street. Woodland Mosaic Bed 7.

Project Title: Public Gardens as Sentinels against Invasive Plants
additionalCollectorNotes: Curator of the Rock Alpine Garden (Mike Kingten) feels this species has the potential to be invasive. A planting in Northern Colorado at the events center has not persisted or spread, however observations of reseeding (by Nick Courtens, Betty Ford Alpine Gardens) have been made in Vail, Colorado. Whether cold-hardiness is limiting is therefore uncertain. Most plants were successfully removed from the Rock Alpine Garden by digging. Appears as a seedling occasionally. Can heavily reseed.
Site Name: Rock Alpine Garden, South Ledge/SAB: South African Border
locality: Denver Botanic Gardens. 909 York Street. Rock Alpine Garden, South Ledge/SAB: South African Border.

additionalCollectorNotes: On the Minnesota noxious weed list. Has been reseeding very heavily in the Rock Garden. Has exhibited the lag time that some taxa express in that for 20-30 years it was well-behaved. Spreads by seed.
locality: Denver Botanic Gardens. 909 York Street. Rock Alpine Garden Boulder Field.

Project Title: Public Gardens as Sentinels against Invasive Plants
additionalCollectorNotes: On the noxious weed list for several states. Curator of the Rock Alpine Garden (Mike Kintgen) feels this plant has the potential to be invasive based on his experience growing it in his gardens. Has been observed escaping along Colorado Blvd and I-25 in a drainage ditch and in parking lot at O'Tooles in Littleton, Colorado. Large populations recently documented at Rocky Ford State Wildlife Area in Otero County, Colorado. Spreads by seed.
locality: Denver Botanic Gardens. 909 York Street. Water Smart Garden, Bed 6.
